# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: preconditioning-numerical
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] In numerical analysis, the **condition number** of a function measures how much the output value of the function can change for a small change in the input argument.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] This is used to measure how sensitive a function is to changes or errors in the input, and how much error in the output results from an error in the input.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Very frequently, one is solving the inverse problem: given $f(x)=y,$ one is solving for *x,* and thus the condition number of the (local) inverse must be used.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number is derived from the theory of propagation of uncertainty, and is formally defined as the value of the asymptotic worst-case relative change in output for a relative change in input.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The "function" is the solution of a problem and the "arguments" are the data in the problem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number is frequently applied to questions in linear algebra, in which case the derivative is straightforward but the error could be in many different directions, and is thus computed from the geometry of the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] More generally, condition numbers can be defined for non-linear functions in several variables.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] A problem with a low condition number is said to be ***well-conditioned***, while a problem with a high condition number is said to be ***ill-conditioned***.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] In non-mathematical terms, an ill-conditioned problem is one where, for a small change in the inputs (the independent variables) there is a large change in the answer or dependent variable.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] This means that the correct solution/answer to the equation becomes hard to find.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number is a property of the problem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Paired with the problem are any number of algorithms that can be used to solve the problem, that is, to calculate the solution.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Some algorithms have a property called *backward stability*; in general, a backward stable algorithm can be expected to accurately solve well-conditioned problems.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Numerical analysis textbooks give formulas for the condition numbers of problems and identify known backward stable algorithms.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] As a rule of thumb, if the condition number $\kappa (A)=10^{k}$ , then up to k digits of accuracy may be lost on top of what would be lost to the numerical method due to loss of precision from arithmetic methods.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] However, the condition number does not give the exact value of the maximum inaccuracy that may occur in the algorithm.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] It generally just bounds it with an estimate (whose computed value depends on the choice of the norm to measure the inaccuracy).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] For example, the condition number associated with the linear equation *Ax* = *b* gives a bound on how inaccurate the solution *x* will be after approximation.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Note that this is before the effects of round-off error are taken into account; conditioning is a property of the matrix, not the algorithm or floating-point accuracy of the computer used to solve the corresponding system.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] In particular, one should think of the condition number as being (very roughly) the rate at which the solution *x* will change with respect to a change in *b*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Thus, if the condition number is large, even a small error in *b* may cause a large error in *x*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] On the other hand, if the condition number is small, then the error in *x* will not be much bigger than the error in *b*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number is defined more precisely to be the maximum ratio of the relative error in *x* to the relative error in *b*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Assuming that *A* is a nonsingular matrix, the error in the solution *A*−1*b* is *A*−1*e*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number may also be infinite, but this implies that the problem is ill-posed (does not possess a unique, well-defined solution for each choice of data; that is, the matrix is not invertible), and no algorithm can be expected to reliably find a solution.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The definition of the condition number depends on the choice of norm, as can be illustrated by two examples.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] where $\sigma _{\text{max}}(A)$ and $\sigma _{\text{min}}(A)$ are maximal and minimal singular values of A respectively.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number with respect to *L*2 arises so often in numerical linear algebra that it is given a name, the **condition number of a matrix**.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] recalling that the eigenvalues of any triangular matrix are simply the diagonal entries.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] If the condition number is not significantly larger than one, the matrix is well-conditioned, which means that its inverse can be computed with good accuracy.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] If the condition number is very large, then the matrix is said to be ill-conditioned.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Practically, such a matrix is almost singular, and the computation of its inverse, or solution of a linear system of equations is prone to large numerical errors.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] A matrix that is not invertible is often said to have a condition number equal to infinity.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Alternatively, it can be defined as $\kappa (A)=\|A\|\|A^{\dagger }\|$ , where $A^{\dagger }$ is the Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] For square matrices, this unfortunately makes the condition number discontinuous, but it is a useful definition for rectangular matrices, which are never invertible but are still used to define systems of equations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Condition numbers can also be defined for nonlinear functions, and can be computed using calculus.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The condition number varies with the point; in some cases one can use the maximum (or supremum) condition number over the domain of the function or domain of the question as an overall condition number, while in other cases the condition number at a particular point is of more interest.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The *relative* condition number of f as a function is $\left|xf'/f\right|$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Note that this is the absolute value of the elasticity of a function in economics.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Most elegantly, this can be understood as (the absolute value of) the ratio of the logarithmic derivative of f , which is $(\log f)'=f'/f$ , and the logarithmic derivative of x , which is $(\log x)'=x'/x=1/x$ , yielding a ratio of $xf'/f$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] This is because the logarithmic derivative is the infinitesimal rate of relative change in a function: it is the derivative $f'$ scaled by the value of f .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Note that if a function has a zero at a point, its condition number at the point is infinite, as infinitesimal changes in the input can change the output from zero to positive or negative, yielding a ratio with zero in the denominator, hence infinite relative change.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] More directly, given a small change $\Delta x$ in x , the relative change in x is $[(x+\Delta x)-x]/x=(\Delta x)/x$ , while the relative change in $f(x)$ is $[f(x+\Delta x)-f(x)]/f(x)$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] The last term is the difference quotient (the slope of the secant line), and taking the limit yields the derivative.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Condition numbers of common elementary functions are particularly important in computing significant figures and can be computed immediately from the derivative.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] Condition numbers can be defined for any function f mapping its data from some domain (e.g. an m -tuple of real numbers x ) into some codomain (e.g. an n -tuple of real numbers $f(x)$ ), where both the domain and codomain are Banach spaces.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] They express how sensitive that function is to small changes (or small errors) in its arguments.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] This is crucial in assessing the sensitivity and potential accuracy difficulties of numerous computational problems, for example, polynomial root finding or computing eigenvalues.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] where $\|\cdot \|$ is a norm on the domain/codomain of f .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/condition-number] where ⁠ $J(x)$ ⁠ denotes the Jacobian matrix of partial derivatives of f at x , and $\|J(x)\|$ is the induced norm on the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] In mathematics, a square matrix is said to be **diagonally dominant** if, for every row of the matrix, the magnitude of the diagonal entry in a row is greater than or equal to the sum of the magnitudes of all the other (off-diagonal) entries in that row.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] where $a_{ij}$ denotes the entry in the i th row and j th column.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] This definition uses a weak inequality, and is therefore sometimes called *weak diagonal dominance*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] If a strict inequality (>) is used, this is called *strict diagonal dominance*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] The unqualified term *diagonal dominance* can mean both strict and weak diagonal dominance, depending on the context.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] The definition in the first paragraph sums entries across each row.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] It is therefore sometimes called *row diagonal dominance*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] If one changes the definition to sum down each column, this is called *column diagonal dominance*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Any strictly diagonally dominant matrix is trivially a weakly chained diagonally dominant matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Weakly chained diagonally dominant matrices are non-singular and include the family of *irreducibly diagonally dominant* matrices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] These are irreducible matrices that are weakly diagonally dominant, but strictly diagonally dominant in at least one row.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] That is, the first and third rows fail to satisfy the diagonal dominance condition.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] The following results can be proved trivially from Gershgorin's circle theorem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Gershgorin's circle theorem itself has a very short proof.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] A strictly diagonally dominant matrix (or an irreducibly diagonally dominant matrix) is non-singular.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] A Hermitian diagonally dominant matrix A with real non-negative diagonal entries is positive semidefinite.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] This follows from the eigenvalues being real, and Gershgorin's circle theorem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] If the symmetry requirement is eliminated, such a matrix is not necessarily positive semidefinite.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] However, the real parts of its eigenvalues remain non-negative by Gershgorin's circle theorem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Similarly, a Hermitian strictly diagonally dominant matrix with real positive diagonal entries is positive definite.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] No (partial) pivoting is necessary for a strictly column diagonally dominant matrix when performing Gaussian elimination (LU factorization).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] The Jacobi and Gauss–Seidel methods for solving a linear system converge if the matrix is strictly (or irreducibly) diagonally dominant.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Many matrices that arise in finite element methods are diagonally dominant.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] A slight variation on the idea of diagonal dominance is used to prove that the pairing on diagrams without loops in the Temperley–Lieb algebra is non-degenerate.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] For a matrix with polynomial entries, one sensible definition of diagonal dominance is if the highest power of q appearing in each row appears only on the diagonal.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] Any strictly diagonally dominant complex square matrix is non-singular (invertible).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] This is also known as Lévy-Desplanques theorem, whose practical applications are found in array signal processing problems such as source enumeration.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/diagonally-dominant-matrix] The Lévy-Desplanques theorem is equivalent to the Gerschgorin circle theorem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] In numerical analysis, an **incomplete Cholesky factorization** of a symmetric positive definite matrix is a sparse approximation of the Cholesky factorization.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] An incomplete Cholesky factorization is often used as a preconditioner for algorithms like the conjugate gradient method.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The Cholesky factorization of a positive definite matrix *A* of order *N* is *A* = *LL** where *L* is a lower triangular matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] An incomplete Cholesky factorization is given by a lower triangular matrix *K* that is sparser than *L*, but in some sense similar to *L*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The corresponding preconditioner is *KK**.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] There are many ways of constructing incomplete Cholesky factorizations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] However, by applying Cholesky decomposition, we observe that some zero elements in the original matrix end up being non-zero elements in the decomposed matrix, like elements (4,2), (5,2) and (5,3) in this example.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] This is not an issue per se, but it is very problematic when working with sparse matrices, since the fill-ins generation is mostly unpredictable and reduces the matrix sparsity, impacting the efficiency of sparse matrix algorithms.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Therefore, given the importance of the Cholesky decomposition in matrix calculations, it is extremely relevant to repurpose the regular method, so as to eliminate the fill-ins generation.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Incomplete Cholesky factorizations do exactly that.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] They yield some matrix $\mathbf {K}$ that is sparser than $\mathbf {L}$ and gives an approximation $\mathbf {A} \approx \mathbf {K} \mathbf {K'}$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] This gives a factor *K* that is as sparse as the lower triangle of *A,* and so storing both *A* and *K* takes at most twice the storage required to store *A* on its own.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The IC(0) algorithm may exit with an error on some positive definite matrices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] It is guaranteed to succeed if *A* is diagonally dominant, although there many positive definite matrices where IC(0) succeeds even without diagonal dominance.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Implementation of the incomplete Cholesky factorization in the GNU Octave language.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The factorization is stored as a lower triangular matrix, with the elements in the upper triangle set to zero.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Consider again the matrix displayed in the motivation section of this article.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] After that, for all the other elements with column greater than 1, calculate (i,j)=(i,j)-(i,1)*(j,1) if (i,1) and (j,1) exist.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The elements (2,2), (4,4), (5,4) and (5,5) (marked with an arrow) have been recalculated, since they obey this rule.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] On the other hand, the elements (3,2), (3,3) and (4,3) won't be recalculated since the element (3,1) doesn't exist, even though the elements (2,1) and (4,1) exist.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Note that in this case no fill-ins were generated compared to the original matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] We get a matrix slightly different from the original one, since the decomposition didn't take into account all the elements, in order to eliminate the fill-ins.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] The sparse version for the incomplete Cholesky factorization (the same procedure presented above) implemented in MATLAB can be seen below.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Naturally, MATLAB has its own means for dealing with sparse matrixes, but the code below was made explicit for pedagogic purposes.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] This algorithm is efficient, since it treats the matrix as a sequential 1D array, automatically avoiding the zero elements.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Initialize a vector *d* to the diagonal of *A*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] We iterate over i from 2 to *N.* At a given iteration *i,* we iterate over *j* from *i+1* to *N,* and downdate $d_{j}=d_{j}-a_{ji}^{2}/d_{i}$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-cholesky-factorization] Note that this downdate can be skipped when $a_{ji}$ is zero.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] In numerical linear algebra, an **incomplete LU factorization** (abbreviated as **ILU**) of a matrix is a sparse approximation of the LU factorization often used as a preconditioner.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Consider a sparse linear system $Ax=b$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] These are often solved by computing the factorization $A=LU$ , with *L* lower unitriangular and *U* upper triangular.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] One then solves $Ly=b$ , $Ux=y$ , which can be done efficiently because the matrices are triangular.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] For a typical sparse matrix, the LU factors can be much less sparse than the original matrix — a phenomenon called *fill-in*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] The memory requirements for using a direct solver can then become a bottleneck in solving linear systems.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] One can combat this problem by using fill-reducing reorderings of the matrix's unknowns, such as the Minimum degree algorithm.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] An incomplete factorization instead seeks triangular matrices *L*, *U* such that $A\approx LU$ rather than $A=LU$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Solving for $LUx=b$ can be done quickly but does not yield the exact solution to $Ax=b$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] So, we instead use the matrix $M=LU$ as a preconditioner in another iterative solution algorithm such as the conjugate gradient method or GMRES.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] is called an **incomplete LU decomposition** (with respect to the sparsity pattern S ).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] The sparsity pattern of *L* and *U* is often chosen to be the same as the sparsity pattern of the original matrix *A*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] If the underlying matrix structure can be referenced by pointers instead of copied, the only extra memory required is for the entries of *L* and *U*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Concerning the stability of the ILU the following theorem was proven by Meijerink and van der Vorst.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Let A be an M-matrix, the (complete) LU decomposition given by $A={\hat {L}}{\hat {U}}$ , and the ILU by $A=LU-R$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Thus, the ILU is at least as stable as the (complete) LU decomposition.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] One can obtain a more accurate preconditioner by allowing some level of extra fill in the factorization.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] A common choice is to use the sparsity pattern of *A2* instead of *A*; this matrix is appreciably more dense than *A*, but still sparse over all.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] One can then generalize this procedure; the ILU(k) preconditioner of a matrix *A* is the incomplete LU factorization with the sparsity pattern of the matrix *Ak+1*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] More accurate ILU preconditioners require more memory, to such an extent that eventually the running time of the algorithm increases even though the total number of iterations decreases.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] Consequently, there is a cost/accuracy trade-off that users must evaluate, typically on a case-by-case basis depending on the family of linear systems to be solved.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/incomplete-lu-factorization] An approximation to the ILU factorization can be performed as a fixed-point iteration in a highly parallel way.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] In mathematics, **preconditioning** is the application of a transformation, called the **preconditioner**, that conditions a given problem into a form that is more suitable for numerical solving methods.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Preconditioning is typically related to reducing a condition number of the problem.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The preconditioned problem is then usually solved by an iterative method.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] In linear algebra and numerical analysis, a **preconditioner** P of a matrix A is a matrix such that $P^{-1}A$ has a smaller condition number than A .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] It is also common to call $T=P^{-1}$ the preconditioner, rather than P , since P itself is rarely explicitly available.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] In modern preconditioning, the application of $T=P^{-1}$ , i.e., multiplication of a column vector, or a block of column vectors, by $T=P^{-1}$ , is commonly performed in a matrix-free fashion, i.e., where neither P , nor $T=P^{-1}$ (and often not even A ) are explicitly available in a matrix form.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Preconditioners are useful in iterative methods to solve a linear system $Ax=b$ for x since the rate of convergence for most iterative linear solvers increases because the condition number of a matrix decreases as a result of preconditioning.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Preconditioned iterative solvers typically outperform direct solvers, e.g., Gaussian elimination, for large, especially for sparse, matrices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Iterative solvers can be used as matrix-free methods, i.e. become the only choice if the coefficient matrix A is not stored explicitly, but is accessed by evaluating matrix-vector products.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Instead of solving the original linear system $Ax=b$ for x , one may consider the **right** preconditioned system $AP^{-1}(Px)=b$ and solve $AP^{-1}y=b$ for y and $Px=y$ for x .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Both systems give the same solution as the original system as long as the preconditioner matrix P is nonsingular.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The left preconditioning is more traditional.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The **two-sided** preconditioned system $QAP^{-1}(Px)=Qb$ may be beneficial, e.g., to preserve the matrix symmetry: if the original matrix A is real symmetric and real preconditioners Q and P satisfy $Q^{T}=P^{-1}$ then the preconditioned matrix $QAP^{-1}$ is also symmetric.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The two-sided preconditioning is common for **diagonal scaling** where the preconditioners Q and P are diagonal and scaling is applied both to columns and rows of the original matrix A , e.g., in order to decrease the dynamic range of entries of the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The goal of preconditioning is reducing the condition number, e.g., of the left or right preconditioned system matrix $P^{-1}A$ or $AP^{-1}$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Small condition numbers benefit fast convergence of iterative solvers and improve stability of the solution with respect to perturbations in the system matrix and the right-hand side, e.g., allowing for more aggressive quantization of the matrix entries using lower computer precision.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The preconditioned matrix $P^{-1}A$ or $AP^{-1}$ is rarely explicitly formed.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Only the action of applying the preconditioner solve operation $P^{-1}$ to a given vector may need to be computed.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Typically there is a trade-off in the choice of P .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Since the operator $P^{-1}$ must be applied at each step of the iterative linear solver, it should have a small cost (computing time) of applying the $P^{-1}$ operation.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The cheapest preconditioner would therefore be $P=I$ since then $P^{-1}=I.$ Clearly, this results in the original linear system and the preconditioner does nothing.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] At the other extreme, the choice $P=A$ gives $P^{-1}A=AP^{-1}=I,$ which has optimal condition number of 1, requiring a single iteration for convergence; however in this case $P^{-1}=A^{-1},$ and applying the preconditioner is as difficult as solving the original system.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] One therefore chooses P as somewhere between these two extremes, in an attempt to achieve a minimal number of linear iterations while keeping the operator $P^{-1}$ as simple as possible.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Some examples of typical preconditioning approaches are detailed below.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Examples of popular preconditioned iterative methods for linear systems include the preconditioned conjugate gradient method, the biconjugate gradient method, and generalized minimal residual method.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] A stationary iterative method is determined by the matrix splitting $A=M-N$ and the iteration matrix $C=I-M^{-1}A$ .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] For a symmetric positive definite matrix A the preconditioner P is typically chosen to be symmetric positive definite as well.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The preconditioned operator $P^{-1}A$ is then also symmetric positive definite, but with respect to the P -based scalar product.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] In this case, the desired effect in applying a preconditioner is to make the quadratic form of the preconditioned operator $P^{-1}A$ with respect to the P -based scalar product to be nearly spherical.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Denoting $T=P^{-1}$ , we highlight that preconditioning is practically implemented as multiplying some vector r by T , i.e., computing the product $Tr.$ In many applications, T is not given as a matrix, but rather as an operator $T(r)$ acting on the vector r .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Some popular preconditioners, however, change with r and the dependence on r may not be linear.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Typical examples involve using non-linear iterative methods, e.g., the conjugate gradient method, as a part of the preconditioner construction.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Such preconditioners may be practically very efficient, however, their behavior is hard to predict theoretically.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] One interesting particular case of variable preconditioning is random preconditioning, e.g., multigrid preconditioning on random coarse grids.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] If used in gradient descent methods, random preconditioning can be viewed as an implementation of stochastic gradient descent and can lead to faster convergence, compared to fixed preconditioning, since it breaks the asymptotic "zig-zag" pattern of the gradient descent.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The most common use of preconditioning is for iterative solution of linear systems resulting from approximations of partial differential equations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The better the approximation quality, the larger the matrix size is.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] In such a case, the goal of optimal preconditioning is, on the one side, to make the spectral condition number of $P^{-1}A$ to be bounded from above by a constant independent of the matrix size, which is called *spectrally equivalent* preconditioning by D'yakonov.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] On the other hand, the cost of application of the $P^{-1}$ should ideally be proportional (also independent of the matrix size) to the cost of multiplication of A by a vector.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The **Sparse Approximate Inverse** preconditioner minimises $\|AT-I\|_{F},$ where $\|\cdot \|_{F}$ is the Frobenius norm and $T=P^{-1}$ is from some suitably constrained set of sparse matrices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Under the Frobenius norm, this reduces to solving numerous independent least-squares problems (one for every column).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] The entries in T must be restricted to some sparsity pattern or the problem remains as difficult and time-consuming as finding the exact inverse of A .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/preconditioner] Huckle together with an approach to selecting sparsity patterns.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] The **Schur complement** is a key tool in the fields of linear algebra, the theory of matrices, numerical analysis, and statistics.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] Suppose *p*, *q* are nonnegative integers such that *p + q > 0*, and suppose *A*, *B*, *C*, *D* are respectively *p* × *p*, *p* × *q*, *q* × *p*, and *q* × *q* matrices of complex numbers.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] The Schur complement is named after Issai Schur who used it to prove Schur's lemma, although it had been used previously.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] Emilie Virginia Haynsworth was the first to call it the *Schur complement*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] The Schur complement is sometimes referred to as the *Feshbach map* after a physicist Herman Feshbach.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] The Schur complement arises when performing a block Gaussian elimination on the matrix *M*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] As a result, the Schur complement $M/D=A-BD^{-1}C$ appears in the upper-left *p*×*p* block.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] An equivalent derivation can be done with the roles of *A* and *D* interchanged.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] By equating the expressions for *M*−1 obtained in these two different ways, one can establish the matrix inversion lemma, which relates the two Schur complements of *M*: *M/D* and *M/A* (see *"Derivation from LDU decomposition"* in Woodbury matrix identity § Alternative proofs).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] which generalizes the determinant formula for 2 × 2 matrices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] Assuming that the submatrix A is invertible, we can eliminate x from the equations, as follows.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] We refer to this as the *reduced equation* obtained by eliminating x from the original equation.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] In particular, we see that the Schur complement is the inverse of the $2,2$ block entry of the inverse of M .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] In practice, one needs A to be well-conditioned in order for this algorithm to be numerically accurate.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] This method is useful in electrical engineering to reduce the dimension of a network's equations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] It is especially useful when element(s) of the output vector are zero.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] For example, when u or v is zero, we can eliminate the associated rows of the coefficient matrix without any changes to the rest of the output vector.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] If v is null then the above equation for x reduces to $x=\left(A^{-1}+A^{-1}BS^{-1}CA^{-1}\right)u$ , thus reducing the dimension of the coefficient matrix while leaving u unmodified.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] This is used to advantage in electrical engineering where it is referred to as node elimination or Kron reduction.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] where ${\textstyle A\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times n}}$ is the covariance matrix of *X*, ${\textstyle C\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times m}}$ is the covariance matrix of *Y* and ${\textstyle B\in \mathbb {R} ^{n\times m}}$ is the covariance matrix between *X* and *Y*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] If we take the matrix $\Sigma$ above to be, not a covariance of a random vector, but a *sample* covariance, then it may have a Wishart distribution.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] In that case, the Schur complement of *C* in $\Sigma$ also has a Wishart distribution.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] The first and third statements can also be derived by considering the minimizer of the quantity $u^{\mathrm {T} }Au+2v^{\mathrm {T} }B^{\mathrm {T} }u+v^{\mathrm {T} }Cv,\,$ as a function of *v* (for fixed *u*).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] There is also a sufficient and necessary condition for the positive semi-definiteness of *X* in terms of a generalized Schur complement.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/schur-complement] where $A^{g}$ denotes a generalized inverse of A .
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] In numerical analysis and scientific computing, a **sparse matrix** or **sparse array** is a matrix in which most of the elements are zero.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] There is no strict definition regarding the proportion of zero-value elements for a matrix to qualify as **sparse** but a common criterion is that the number of non-zero elements is roughly equal to the number of rows or columns.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if most of the elements are non-zero, the matrix is considered **dense**.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The number of zero-valued elements divided by the total number of elements (e.g., *m* × *n* for an *m* × *n* matrix) is sometimes referred to as the **sparsity** of the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Conceptually, sparsity corresponds to systems with few pairwise interactions.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] For example, consider a line of balls connected by springs from one to the next: this is a sparse system, as only adjacent balls are coupled.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] By contrast, if the same line of balls were to have springs connecting each ball to all other balls, the system would correspond to a dense matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The concept of sparsity is useful in combinatorics and application areas such as network theory and numerical analysis, which typically have a low density of significant data or connections.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Large sparse matrices often appear in scientific or engineering applications when solving partial differential equations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] When storing and manipulating sparse matrices on a computer, it is beneficial and often necessary to use specialized algorithms and data structures that take advantage of the sparse structure of the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Specialized computers have been made for sparse matrices, as they are common in the machine learning field.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Operations using standard dense-matrix structures and algorithms are slow and inefficient when applied to large sparse matrices as processing and memory are wasted on the zeros.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Sparse data is by nature more easily compressed and thus requires significantly less storage.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Some very large sparse matrices are infeasible to manipulate using standard dense-matrix algorithms.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The band matrices form a special class of sparse matrix where the non-zero elements are concentrated near the main diagonal.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A band matrix is characterised by its lower and upper bandwidths, which refer to the number of diagonals below and above (respectively) the main diagonal between which all of the non-zero entries are contained.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Formally, the lower bandwidth of a matrix **A** is the smallest number *p* such that the entry *a**i*,*j* vanishes whenever *i* > *j* + *p*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Similarly, the upper bandwidth is the smallest number *p* such that *a**i*,*j* = 0 whenever *i* < *j* − *p* (Golub & Van Loan 1996, §1.2.1).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] For example, a tridiagonal matrix has lower bandwidth 1 and upper bandwidth 1.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] As another example, the following sparse matrix has lower and upper bandwidth both equal to 3.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Matrices with reasonably small upper and lower bandwidth are known as band matrices and often lend themselves to simpler algorithms than general sparse matrices; or one can sometimes apply dense matrix algorithms and gain efficiency simply by looping over a reduced number of indices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] By rearranging the rows and columns of a matrix **A** it may be possible to obtain a matrix **A**′ with a lower bandwidth.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A number of algorithms are designed for bandwidth minimization.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix is the extreme case of a band matrix, with zero upper and lower bandwidth.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A diagonal matrix can be stored efficiently by storing just the entries in the main diagonal as a one-dimensional array, so a diagonal *n* × *n* matrix requires only *n* entries in memory.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A symmetric sparse matrix arises as the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph; it can be stored efficiently as an adjacency list.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A block-diagonal matrix consists of sub-matrices along its diagonal blocks.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The *fill-in* of a matrix are those entries that change from an initial zero to a non-zero value during the execution of an algorithm.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] To reduce the memory requirements and the number of arithmetic operations used during an algorithm, it is useful to minimize the fill-in by switching rows and columns in the matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The symbolic Cholesky decomposition can be used to calculate the worst possible fill-in before doing the actual Cholesky decomposition.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] There are other methods than the Cholesky decomposition in use.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Orthogonalization methods (such as QR factorization) are common, for example, when solving problems by least squares methods.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] While the theoretical fill-in is still the same, in practical terms the "false non-zeros" can be different for different methods.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] And symbolic versions of those algorithms can be used in the same manner as the symbolic Cholesky to compute worst case fill-in.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Both iterative and direct methods exist for sparse matrix solving.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Iterative methods, such as conjugate gradient method and GMRES utilize fast computations of matrix-vector products $Ax_{i}$ , where matrix A is sparse.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The use of preconditioners can significantly accelerate convergence of such iterative methods.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] A matrix is typically stored as a two-dimensional array.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Each entry in the array represents an element *a**i*,*j* of the matrix and is accessed by the two indices *i* and *j*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Conventionally, *i* is the row index, numbered from top to bottom, and *j* is the column index, numbered from left to right.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] For an *m* × *n* matrix, the amount of memory required to store the matrix in this format is proportional to *m* × *n* (disregarding the fact that the dimensions of the matrix also need to be stored).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] In the case of a sparse matrix, substantial memory requirement reductions can be realized by storing only the non-zero entries.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Depending on the number and distribution of the non-zero entries, different data structures can be used and yield huge savings in memory when compared to the basic approach.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The trade-off is that accessing the individual elements becomes more complex and additional structures are needed to be able to recover the original matrix unambiguously.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] DOK consists of a dictionary that maps (row, column)-pairs to the value of the elements.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Elements that are missing from the dictionary are taken to be zero.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The format is good for incrementally constructing a sparse matrix in random order, but poor for iterating over non-zero values in lexicographical order.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] One typically constructs a matrix in this format and then converts to another more efficient format for processing.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] LIL stores one list per row, with each entry containing the column index and the value.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Typically, these entries are kept sorted by column index for faster lookup.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] This is another format good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] COO stores a list of (row, column, value) tuples.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Ideally, the entries are sorted first by row index and then by column index, to improve random access times.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] This is another format that is good for incremental matrix construction.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The *compressed sparse row* (CSR) or *compressed row storage* (CRS) or Yale format represents a matrix **M** by three (one-dimensional) arrays, that respectively contain nonzero values, the extents of rows, and column indices.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] It is similar to COO, but compresses the row indices, hence the name.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] This format allows fast row access and matrix-vector multiplications (**M***x*).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The CSR format has been in use since at least the mid-1960s, with the first complete description appearing in 1967.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The CSR format stores a sparse *m* × *n* matrix **M** in row form using three (one-dimensional) arrays (V, COL_INDEX, ROW_INDEX).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Let NNZ denote the number of nonzero entries in **M**.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Then we take slices from V and COL_INDEX starting at row_start and ending at row_end.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] To extract the row 1 (the second row) of this matrix we set `row_start=1` and `row_end=2`.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] We now know that in row 1 we have one element at column 1 with value 8.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] In this case the CSR representation contains 13 entries, compared to 16 in the original matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The CSR format saves on memory only when NNZ < (*m* (*n* − 1) − 1) / 2.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The whole is stored as 21 entries: 8 in V, 8 in COL_INDEX, and 5 in ROW_INDEX.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Note that in this format, the first value of ROW_INDEX is always zero and the last is always NNZ, so they are in some sense redundant (although in programming languages where the array length needs to be explicitly stored, NNZ would not be redundant).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Nonetheless, this does avoid the need to handle an exceptional case when computing the length of each row, as it guarantees the formula ROW_INDEX[*i* + 1] − ROW_INDEX[*i*] works for any row *i*.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Moreover, the memory cost of this redundant storage is likely insignificant for a sufficiently large matrix.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The (old and new) Yale sparse matrix formats are instances of the CSR scheme.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The old Yale format works exactly as described above, with three arrays; the new format combines ROW_INDEX and COL_INDEX into a single array and handles the diagonal of the matrix separately.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] For logical adjacency matrices, the data array can be omitted, as the existence of an entry in the row array is sufficient to model a binary adjacency relation.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] It is likely known as the Yale format because it was proposed in the 1977 Yale Sparse Matrix Package report from Department of Computer Science at Yale University.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] CSC is similar to CSR except that values are read first by column, a row index is stored for each value, and column pointers are stored.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] For example, CSC is (val, row_ind, col_ptr), where val is an array of the (top-to-bottom, then left-to-right) non-zero values of the matrix; row_ind is the row indices corresponding to the values; and, col_ptr is the list of val indexes where each column starts.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The name is based on the fact that column index information is compressed relative to the COO format.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] One typically uses another format (LIL, DOK, COO) for construction.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] This format is efficient for arithmetic operations, column slicing, and matrix-vector products.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] This is the traditional format for specifying a sparse matrix in MATLAB (via the `sparse` function).
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] Many software libraries support sparse matrices, and provide solvers for sparse matrix equations.
[src:preconditioning-numerical/sparse-matrix] The term *sparse matrix* was possibly coined by Harry Markowitz who initiated some pioneering work but then left the field.
